September 4 at 2:38 PM ·

September is National Suicide Prevention Month. Do not suffer in silence. You always have the choice to reach out in a time of struggle. #suicideprevention

◾️ National Suicide Lifeline: ☎️ 1-800-273-TALK (8255)
◾️ Suicide Crisis Text Line: 📱Text NAMI to 741-741

➡️ For help or any questions, please contact us, Nulton Diagnostic & Treatment Center at 1-888-918-5465 or visit nulton.com.

@lvhealthnetwork is our partner at Northwestern Lehigh and their help with both our return to school and return to sports guidance has been critical in our success. Posted @withregram • @lvhealthnetwork There’s no guidebook to #parenting and there’s certainly no guidebook to parenting during a #pandemic. But Lehigh Valley Reilly Children’s Hospital, @lvhealthnetwork and @coordhealth are here to help. ⁠
⁠
From face mask advice to tips for packing your kid’s lunch, we’ve got information to help you navigate the school year. ⁠
⁠
☝️Check out our stories☝️ and learn more at LVHN.org/schoolpartners.⁠
⁠
#backtoschool #schoolpartners #family #parenthood #newnormal

post_text:
Public Service Announcement for Lynn and Heidelberg residents: URGENT! Heidelberg and Lynn Township residents... did anyone here or do you know anyone who had a foot of water or more in the basement and/or more than an inch of water on the first floor?

Did anyone have damage to the outside of any buildings on their property that was caused by the wind or trees brought down by Isaias?

What about crop damage? Any significant damage to an agricultural or or any other kind of business?

Please respond ASAP. I need to get a damage report to the County. They’re working with PEMA, FEMA, and the Red Cross to get funding to aid in clean up and restoration, but we need to report the damage as soon as possible to qualify.

Thanks for your help! Also, if you need help with supplies for clean up I may be able to help point you in the right direction. I also have information on disinfecting your well and other clean up information if you need it.

post_text: Here’s another frequently asked question: What do students need to bring to school? In addition to traditional school supplies, we need students to bring a backpack, a water bottle, a face covering, and school supplies labeled with their name. Our Back to School Supply Lists are on our school websites. We purchased hand sanitizer from @eightoaksdistillers for each of our classroom and learning spaces. If you would like to send an individual bottle for your child’s use, you may do so. You may also send in disinfectant wipes for your child’s school. We have procured many supplies but assure you we will put them to good use to keep our entire school community safe. Hand sanitizer and disinfectant wipes are purely optional and included to answer some questions we’ve received about ways parents can help. #staykindkeephealthyTOGETHER

post_text: A frequently asked question we receive is what can we do to help? We are working hard to ensure a safe and healthy educational environment for our return to school. You can help us reinforce health and safety guidelines that will keep our entire school community safe. You can help by talking with your child about social distancing and why the school needs to implement different rules for the Fall of 2020. We know everyone doesn’t agree with every rule but your help in enforcing school rules as important to keep everyone safe is very important as we return to school. We appreciate your support and understanding. Stay Kind, Keep Healthy, Together

Thanks to LVHN for the positive message and some thoughts to ponder. Posted @withregram • @lvhealthnetwork We had a special visitor at our offices recently that made us think: What can we learn from the hawk in this time of crisis, chaos and confusion?⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🦅 Hawks soar high in the sky and have the ability to view all of life from this perspective. How can you look at the big picture and not get too wrapped up in the negative today?⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🦅 Hawks represent an ability to lead others and take initiative. Like Gandhi said, “Be the change that you wish to see in the world.” Set an example of safety and others will follow.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🦅 Hawks always observe their area before taking action. When you are visiting retailers or other public places around groups of people, be aware of your surroundings. If the area you are about to enter doesn't seem to be in compliance with safety regulations, don't enter. Help #stopasecondwave.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
Thank you to @powerofpositivity for these fun hawk facts. ⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🤔What do YOU think this hawk is trying to tell us? Leave your encouraging captions in the comments.🤔

post_text:
Pennsylvania Department of Health recommendation for out-of-state travelers as it pertains to Voluntary Summer Sport Workouts:

"If you have traveled or plan to travel, to an area where there are high amounts of COVID-19 cases, it is recommended that you stay at home for 14 days upon return to Pennsylvania. If you travel to the following states, you will need to quarantine for 14 days upon return":

Alabama
Arizona
Arkansas
California
Florida
Georgia
Idaho
Louisiana
Mississippi
Nevada
North Carolina
South Carolina
Tennessee
Texas
Utah

As this pertains to our voluntary summer workouts, any coach or student-athlete who has traveled to one of the aforementioned states, may not participate in our voluntary workouts for a period of 14 days starting on the day they return to Pennsylvania. This goes into effect immediately and until further notice from the Pennsylvania Department of Health.

post_text:
Posted @withregram • @missciterone This year has been a whirlwind and it has finally come to a close. Yesterday we waved and said goodbye to our students as they drove past us in the school parking lot. When I think about the challenges online learning created, I continue to be thankful for the students in my room this year. They dove into virtual learning without any hesitation and continued to show up until the very last day. I know the start of next year will be just as complicated, but we made it this far, so we can do it again! Thank you to all of the staff, parents, and students for being flexible and doing whatever it takes to continue education from home! Until next year... .
.
.
.
#onlinelearning #teachersofinstagram #teachersfollowteachers #summerbreak #sel #virtualteaching #virtuallearning #teacherhacks #teachingonline

post_text:
UPDATE: NWLHS's night to light up the town is JUNE 14th

Starting next week, all downtown Allentown buildings will be lit up in support of the Lehigh Valley's #Classof2020. Each day buildings will be lit in the colors of one of the 22 area high schools.

The Downtown Allentown business community – led by PPL Corporation and City Center Investment Corp. – will be lighting Allentown’s skyline in school colors nearly every day in June to honor the graduating seniors of the Lehigh Valley’s high schools.

Starting June 1, buildings throughout Downtown Allentown – including the PPL Tower Building, Two City Center, Three City Center, Five City Center and Tower Six – will be lit in school colors to honor each and every high school in Lehigh and Northampton counties. The lighting schedule begins alphabetically with Allentown Central Catholic High School and ends on June 23 with Wilson Area High School. The full schedule is below.

Light it up on June 14th for Northwestern Lehigh’s Class of 2020! 🐯 🎓💛🖤

Share this so we can light up Northwestern Lehigh homes and businesses for the #Classof2020

post_text:
"This shout out goes to not only my personal team (Sara Fitzgerald, Amy Kelly, and Casey Coombs) but to the rest of the 6th grade team (Lou Ann Smacchi, Maureen Roman, Patti Greenawalt, Liz Nemeth, and Matt Fritz). While our individual teams have different personalities and styles, when you put all of us together we make a dynamite working team! Whether we are planning, teaching, or overcoming obstacles, we all work together bringing our own individual strengths to the situation. All of us are vested in doing what is best for our students whether that is transitioning our new 6th graders into the MS, Turkey Trot, Orienteering, end of year activities or the day-to-day teaching. I am so grateful to have had this team upon my return to the MS 9 years ago. Not only are you my colleagues and team, you are all my friends! Happy Teacher Appreciation Week!"
- Kelly Fornauf (Staff Member)

post_text:
"I'd like to recognize Lisa Pollock, a teacher's assistant who has been an essential part of our fifth grade classroom family this school year. Mrs. Pollock is kind, a hard worker, and knowledgeable. Mrs. Pollock works so well in our small groups-- knowing intuitively what a student needs, and building in scaffolds so that each student meets success. Mrs. Pollock is very attune to student needs, and has even brought things in from home to make the student classroom experience richer---plant based straws when we were learning about recycling, machine magazines to assist with a student needing motivation, locks for our escape room, and theme day accessories for students who didn't have any at home. She does this quietly, being truly motivated by helping others. Mrs. Pollock shows Tiger Pride in everything she does. Thank you, Lisa!"
- Angela Rimm (Staff Member)

post_text:
"I'd like to thank Mrs. Chandler for all she does for her students and their families. The entire third grade team is awesome, but my daughter is absolutely loving her time in Mrs. Chandler's class! She was so sad that their time was cut short but Mrs. Chandler helped make the transition to online schooling smooth. The schedule is organized and easy to follow and helps us stay on track. There are zoom sessions several times a week with other special activities thrown in for fun such as their talent show, scavenger hunt and most recently, their lunch bunch. They all ate lunch together and chatted over zoom. She truly cares for all her students and it shows!"
- Elizabeth Earles (Parent)

post_text:
"As you may know, today was “supposed” to be NWE’s Annual Third Grade Musical! Despite not having the chance to put this year’s show on, I want to recognize our production staff for the tremendous amount of work they WERE putting into the show that never was. To Marisa Bartholomew, Jake Bennett, Alissa Cawley, Jodi Chandler, Linda Eberle, Kyle Grim, Sue Hanlon, Lora Krum, Maria Pulli, Tara Reigle, and Tracy Smoyer: You have ALWAYS been supportive of all the crazy ideas and I am so sad we didn’t get to have those moments together this year! Our moment in the spotlight will come again, but till then, you ALL deserve to be recognized for your amazing talents and outstanding work THIS year, too! I miss you all!!"
- Shawn Fies (Staff Member)

I was able to work with such amazing kids to get ready for what's to come in college and beyond as a future educator. "I want to thank Gina Wood for sharing her excitement and passion for creating meaningful and exciting experiences for her ELA students with me. "I would like to recognize my coworker Mrs. Scholl. Mrs. Scholl put her all into researching and learning about best practice strategies for helping students who had academic challenges, and then used this information to work directly with the students in engaging, fun, and effective ways. Dianne is such a problem solver, and has helped our Weisenberg staff to feel comfortable incorporating new technology, because we know she will be there to help and support on site. She is calm, and can figure out anything! She is such an advocate for teaching in innovative ways to keep our students growing! Kelly has been such a valuable resource in finding new platforms and tools, and training staff to use them, in such an encouraging way. She is the perfect tech coach--knowledgeable and team oriented. Both of these ladies are just genuinely good people. Both Dianne and Kelly are there to support any project that any teacher wants to try, and they use their creative problem solving to make our shared Tiger vision a reality. I just love and respect both of these Tigers. Thank you, Ladies!"
- Angela Rimm (Staff Member)

post_text:
"Karen Rex is not only an amazing teacher for her students but also a dedicated mentor to many teachers as well. Even when trying to figure out a completely new form of teaching for herself, she provided countless hours of support to her teammates so we could all rise to meet the challenge we are facing. She makes herself available to help any time when she is needed. But what I love most about Karen is her humility. I asked Karen for guidance every step of the way and almost always she knew the direction to provide. But even in those rare moments when she did not, she provided reassurance and said she would use her time to research my question so I did not have to stress about it. Thank you, Karen Rex: amazing teacher and dedicated mentor!"
- Michelle Slack (Staff Member)
